Some people, with a gift for serendipity, stumble upon bright new ideas without being aware of their novelty. The princeps of the

Italian humanists of the early Renaissance, Leon Battista Alberti, however, was not that kind of man; on the contrary, if we take a look at his writings on art theory, at least, he always seems keenly aware of his innovations, judging from his open or disguised criticism and polemics against his predecessors or contemporaries of a more conservative observation.
